Subject: Wipe stale EVDI /dev/dri/cardN entries on driver open & close

libevdi's evdi_disconnect() only flips the connector state to disconnected;
it does NOT remove /dev/dri/cardN. The card stays around until something
writes "1" to /sys/devices/evdi/remove_all (or the kernel module is
unloaded).

Combined with patch 0004 (kmsgrab now accepts EVDI cards in its fallback
path), this means: if Apollo is restarted while an EVDI card from a prior
session is still in /dev/dri/, the new Apollo's encoder-probe sequence at
startup hits that stale card and tries to gbm_create_device() on it. Mesa
SIGSEGVs inside libgallium during DRI screen init because EVDI has no
render node and isn't a real GPU. Apollo crashes during start-pre, the
Steam Deck client gets "Connection Refused".

Repro before this patch:

  1. apollo running, Steam Deck streams (creates EVDI card0).
  2. Steam Deck disconnects → removeVirtualDisplay calls evdi.disconnect +
     evdi.close. /dev/dri/card0 (EVDI) survives.
  3. `systemctl --user restart apollo` (or any apollo restart).
  4. New apollo, encoder probe, mesa SIGSEGV in gbm_create_device on card0.
  5. `apollo.service: Failed with result 'core-dump'`. Service flaps.

Fix: write "1" to /sys/devices/evdi/remove_all at both ends of the VDISPLAY
driver lifecycle:

  - openVDisplayDevice(): cleans up any leftover from a crashed prior run
    BEFORE Apollo's kmsgrab probes /dev/dri/*.
  - closeVDisplayDevice(): cleans up our own cards on normal shutdown so we
    leave a clean tree for the next startup.

Also unregister the per-display libevdi buffer (registered by patch 0005)
inside closeVDisplayDevice's loop, so the kernel doesn't keep a reference
to memory we're about to free.

The remove_all sysfs file is mode 0220 group=video thanks to evdi-perms.service
shipped with this package, so apollo (uid in video group) can write to it
without needing CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE.

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -928,6 +928,32 @@
     }
   }
 
+  // Clear any leftover EVDI /dev/dri/cardN entries from a previous Apollo
+  // run that didn't clean up (crash, hard restart, etc.). evdi_disconnect()
+  // alone leaves the cardN file in place; only writing "1" to
+  // /sys/devices/evdi/remove_all actually removes it. Without this, mesa's
+  // libgbm crashes inside gbm_create_device when Apollo's kmsgrab probes
+  // /dev/dri/* at startup with a stale EVDI card still present.
+  //
+  // Safe even if no EVDI devices exist (count=0 just returns ENODEV-like
+  // success). Best-effort: ignore write errors so this never blocks startup.
+  static void cleanup_stale_evdi_devices() {
+    const char *path = "/sys/devices/evdi/remove_all";
+    int fd = ::open(path, O_WRONLY | O_CLOEXEC);
+    if (fd < 0) {
+      BOOST_LOG(debug) << "[VDISPLAY] Couldn't open " << path << " for cleanup: " << strerror(errno);
+      return;
+    }
+    const char one = '1';
+    ssize_t n = ::write(fd, &one, 1);
+    if (n < 0) {
+      BOOST_LOG(debug) << "[VDISPLAY] write to " << path << " failed: " << strerror(errno);
+    } else {
+      BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] Cleared any stale EVDI /dev/dri/cardN entries.";
+    }
+    ::close(fd);
+  }
+
   DRIVER_STATUS openVDisplayDevice() {
     std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(vdisplay_mutex);
 
@@ -937,6 +963,13 @@
 
     BOOST_LOG(info) << "[VDISPLAY] Initializing Linux virtual display driver...";
 
+    // Before we let Apollo's kmsgrab probe /dev/dri/* (which happens during
+    // encoder testing right after this returns), wipe any leftover EVDI
+    // cards. Without this, mesa libgbm SIGSEGVs on a stale EVDI card and
+    // Apollo never reaches the "listening" state, so Steam Deck clients see
+    // "Connection Refused".
+    cleanup_stale_evdi_devices();
+
     // Try to load EVDI library
     evdi_available = load_evdi_library();
 
@@ -994,6 +1027,10 @@
     for (auto &[guid, vdinfo] : virtual_displays) {
       if (vdinfo.active) {
         if (vdinfo.using_evdi && vdinfo.handle) {
+          if (vdinfo.evdi_buf_id > 0) {
+            evdi.unregister_buffer(vdinfo.handle, vdinfo.evdi_buf_id);
+            vdinfo.evdi_buf_id = 0;
+          }
           evdi.disconnect(vdinfo.handle);
           evdi.close(vdinfo.handle);
         }
@@ -1004,6 +1041,12 @@
     }
     virtual_displays.clear();
 
+    // Actually remove the EVDI /dev/dri/cardN entries we created, so a
+    // restart of Apollo starts with a clean /dev/dri/. evdi_disconnect only
+    // marks the connector disconnected — the cardN device persists until
+    // we write to /sys/devices/evdi/remove_all.
+    cleanup_stale_evdi_devices();
+
     // Unload EVDI library
     unload_evdi_library();
 
